05059nam a22005895i 9780226181608DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014008019  a9780226181608  a(DE-B1597)523503  a(OCoLC)894555003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHJ249b.E35 2014 4aHJ249b.E35 2015 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a336.73090342231 aEdling, Max M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Hercules in the Cradle :bWar, Money, and the American State, 1783-1867 /cMax M. Edling. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b10 line drawings, 17 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Beginnings, 1500-190000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: War, Money, and American History -- tChapter one. A More Effectual Mode of Administration: The Constitution and the Origins of American Public Finance -- tChapter two. The Soul of Government: Creating an American Fiscal Regime -- tChapter three. So Immense a Power in the Affairs of War: The Restoration of Public Credit -- tChapter four. Equal to the Severest Trials: Mr. Madison’s War -- tChapter five. The Two Most Powerful Republics in the World: Mr. Polk’s War -- tChapter six. A Rank among the Very First of Military Powers: Mr. Lincoln’s War -- tConclusion. The Ideology, Structure, and Significance of the First American Fiscal Regime -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwo and a half centuries after the American Revolution the United States stands as one of the greatest powers on earth and the undoubted leader of the western hemisphere. This stupendous evolution was far from a foregone conclusion at independence. The conquest of the North American continent required violence, suffering, and bloodshed. It also required the creation of a national government strong enough to go to war against, and acquire territory from, its North American rivals. In A Hercules in the Cradle, Max M. Edling argues that the federal government’s abilities to tax and to borrow money, developed in the early years of the republic, were critical to the young nation’s ability to wage war and expand its territory. He traces the growth of this capacity from the time of the founding to the aftermath of the Civil War, including the funding of the War of 1812 and the Mexican War. Edling maintains that the Founding Fathers clearly understood the connection between public finance and power: a well-managed public debt was a key part of every modern state. Creating a debt would always be a delicate and contentious matter in the American context, however, and statesmen of all persuasions tried to pay down the national debt in times of peace. A Hercules in the Cradle explores the origin and evolution of American public finance and shows how the nation’s rise to great-power status in the nineteenth century rested on its ability to go into debt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFinance, PubliczUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aFinance, PubliczUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aFiscal policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aFiscal policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWarxEconomic aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aWarxEconomic aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  anorth american history, historical research, revolutionary war, united states of america, western, independence, violence, wartime, territory, federal government, governing, politics, political, tax, money, economics, founding fathers, public finances, debt, 19th century, fiscal policy, administration, constit